<TITLE> India to allow France's Dassault bid for fighters </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Wed May 27,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India has reversed a decision blocking France's Dassault Aviation from bidding for a $10.4 billion fighter jets deal after the company clarified technical details, India's air force chief said on Wednesday. The contract for 126 multi-role warplanes is one of the world's biggest arms deals. "They have answered and clarified certain points." Fali Homi Major, India's air force chief, told reporters. Bids were submitted last year from Boeing and Lockheed Martin Corp, Russia's MiG-35, Saab's KAS-39 Gripen and the Eurofighter Typhoon, backed by a consortium of British, German, Italian and Spanish companies. Dassault was barred in April after the military said there were unanswered technical questions about its Rafale warjet. India and France signed a civilian nuclear deal and have spoken of widening their bilateral relations. India has said it will soon begin trials of the fighter jets. India plans to spend more than $30 billion over the next five years to modernise its largely Soviet-era weapons sys
